>Description:
>How-To-Repeat:
(define f (new frame% (label "")))
(define mb (new menu-bar% (parent f)))
(define m (new menu% (label "file") (parent mb)))
(define mi1 (new menu-item% 
                 (parent m)
                 (label "close")
                 (shortcut #\w)
                 (callback (lambda (x y) (printf "close\n")))))
(define mi2 (new menu-item%
                 (parent m)
                 (label "close tab")
                 (shortcut #f)
                 (callback (lambda (x y) (printf "close tab\n")))))
(send mi2 enable #f)
(send mi2 set-shortcut #\w)
(send mi1 set-shortcut #f)
(send mi2 enable #t)
(send f show #t)

run the above. the menus show that that <menukey>-w should
run the close tab shortcut and, when typing <menukey>-w, 
the menubar does indeed flash (as it should) but the 
callback isn't invoked.
>Fix:
>Audit-Trail:
State changed from "open" to "closed" by mflatt at Fri, 23 Dec 2005 08:59:01 -0500
Reason>>> `set-shortcut' wasn't doing anything when the item is
disabled, but since disable menu items now retain keybindings,
`set-shortcut' needed to proceed as if the item is enabled

